%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Conclusion}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:conclusion}

%claude:
You now know how [[mk]] works, from parsing an [[mkfile]] through
building a dependency graph to scheduling parallel jobs.
The pipeline --- parse, evaluate, build graph, find outdated files,
schedule recipes --- is a clean decomposition where each stage
produces well-defined data structures consumed by the next.
%claude:
The OCaml implementation brings several advantages over the original
C version: the separation of parsing and evaluation makes the code
easier to understand; algebraic types make the different stages
(parsed words vs.\ evaluated patterns vs.\ concrete strings) explicit
in the type system; and the capability system documents exactly what
system resources each function needs.
%claude:
For the original C implementation of [[mk]], see \book{Make} which
covers the same program with the same chapter structure.
For the shell that [[mk]] invokes to execute recipes, see \book{Shell}.

